				<div class=3D"entry-content">
					<p>When I=E2=80=99m knitting other designers=E2=80=99 patterns, I very=
 often end in the dilemma of my gauge not matching the pattern (but having =
the perfect drape and feel), or the yarn I want to use not being the right =
weight. It=E2=80=99s silly, I know =E2=80=93 I could change yarns or needle=
s or something, but very often I don=E2=80=99t want to. What to do, then?</=
p>
<p>Well, sometimes I recalculate. But often, there is a pretty simple way o=
f =E2=80=9Caltering=E2=80=9D the pattern, which I=E2=80=99d like to share w=
ith you!</p>
<p>I have an example of a project I did a while ago: <a href=3D"https://www=
.ravelry.com/patterns/library/fuse" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noopener">The =
Fuse cardigan by Veronik Avery</a>.</p>
<p><a href=3D"https://www.ravelry.com/projects/dutte/fuse"><img decoding=3D=
"async" class=3D"aligncenter size-full wp-image-750" src=3D"https://knitter=
skitchen.com/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/fuse-cardigan.jpg" alt=3D=
"Fuse cardigan" width=3D"371" height=3D"500"></a></p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>It is originally done in worsted weight yarn on a 5,5 mm / US 9 needle, =
but I just had this perfect yarn in fingering weight. Also, I didn=E2=80=99=
t really want a chunky cardigan, but instead more of a light weight one. Us=
ing fingering weight yarn on those large needles would make the cardi way t=
oo floppy and loose though, so I decided to work on 4 m / US 6 needles inst=
ead.</p>
<p>You can probably guess that if I just made my regular size (size M/37=E2=
=80=B3 bust), I would end up with a much smaller garment. When you work on =
smaller needles and with thinner yarn, your gauge becomes tighter, so it ta=
kes more stitches per 10 cm / 4 inches.</p>
<blockquote><p>The golden rule of (stitch) gauge:<br>
More sts on 10 cm -&gt; tighter gauge, smaller item. Often worked on smalle=
r needles.<br>
Less sts on 10 cm -&gt; looser gauge, bigger item. Often worked on bigger n=
eedles.</p></blockquote>
<p>As my gauge would be tighter (smaller needles + thinner yarn =3D more st=
s per 10 cm/4=E2=80=B3), I could either choose to recalculate everything (!=
), or choose to make a bigger size to compensate for the missing width of t=
he fabric. The last option is most likely the most appealing to everyone, i=
sn=E2=80=99t it?</p>
