	<br>
How I went about determining the size I should knit:<p></p>
<p><strong>Step 1: I made a swatch!</strong><br>
I know this seems like a huge hurdle for some, as most people just want to =
get on with knitting the actual garment. However, for garments especially, =
your gauge really is important. See the golden rule of gauge above! <em>If =
the pattern says 10 sts per 10 cm/4=E2=80=B3, and your gauge is 14 sts per =
10 cm/4=E2=80=B3, the number of stitches cast on will become a smaller item=
 than if you had a gauge of 10 sts per 10 cm/4=E2=80=B3.<br>
</em>Also: Make sure to wash and block your swatch before you measure the f=
inal gauge. Gauge can change in washing, depending on how you treat it and =
what the fiber content of the yarn is. Treat your swatch the same way as yo=
u will be treating the finished garment!</p>
<p>So, I made that swatch using fingering weight yarn and 4 mm / US 6 needl=
es.<br>
The pattern called for a gauge of&nbsp;14,5 sts &amp;&nbsp;25,5 rows, my ga=
uge was 20 sts &amp; 35 rows.</p>
<p><strong>Step 2: Calculating the gauge difference</strong><br>
In order to calculate the stitch gauge difference between the two, I did th=
is calculation:</p>
<p>my gauge / pattern gauge =3D difference in gauge (the number of sts in m=
y gauge needed to work 1 st in the pattern gauge)<br>
20 / 14,5 =3D 1,38</p>
<p><strong>Step 3: Calculating the needed size</strong><br>
If I went by the bust size alone, the size I would need (37=E2=80=B3) would=
 correspond to:</p>
<p>My size * gauge difference =3D size I need to work by<br>
38=E2=80=B3*1,38 =3D 52,5=E2=80=B3.</p>
<p>So yes, I would need to work the size that corresponded to a bust size o=
f 52,5=E2=80=B3.<br>
The pattern=E2=80=99s biggest size was 53=E2=80=B3, so that made it clear =
=E2=80=93 that was the size I needed to make! It turned out quite alright, =
didn=E2=80=99t it?</p>
<p><strong>Pitfalls<br>
</strong>HOWEVER, this method only works if you have an overview over the p=
attern and understanding of the garment construction. It=E2=80=99s absolute=
ly the easiest for straight top down or bottom up sweaters and other items,=
 but as soon as they=E2=80=99re worked on the bias (or using other funky te=
chniques) you risk getting in a pickle. I=E2=80=99m not saying it=E2=80=99s=
 impossible, but it depends wholly on the item in question!</p>
<p><strong>A couple of things to note:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>The above method with size change is for <span style=3D"text-decoration=
: underline;">horizontal</span> calculations only (stitch count).</li>
<li>You can do the same for <span style=3D"text-decoration: underline;">ver=
tical</span> calculations (row count), but make sure to consider the differ=
ences that might occur. I was so lucky to have my row gauge vs. the pattern=
 row gauge be the same percentage in difference as the stitch gauge, but th=
at might not always be the case.</li>
<li>When working on something like a sweater, very often it will say to wor=
k to a certain measurement. Use that measurement instead of counting rows!<=
/li>
<li>The garment I did this on had a lot of positive ease. I ended up with l=
ess positive ease than was recommended (me: 1=E2=80=B3, recommended: 6=E2=
=80=B3), as really the size matching a 53=E2=80=B3 bust would have needed t=
o be 59=E2=80=B3 (but the pattern only went up to 53=E2=80=B3). It was no i=
ssue here, but it might be in a more fitted garment!</li>
</ul>
<p>I hope this post&nbsp;has been helpful!</p>
